INSERT INTO "tbl1_site" ("Site_ID", "Administrator", "Modern_composition", "Description_site", "Site_context", "Site_interpretation_keyword", "Site_interpretation", "Date_entry", "description_m_composition", "Description_site_OLD") VALUES (312, NULL, E'0', E'Tumulus shaped funerary monument, no platform visible. Composed of a circular wall filled in with earth. \r\nCircular wall with Opus Caementicium consisting of basalt chips and peperino, with some chalk. Grey mortar is mixed with particles of red tufa (cruma). Wall is most visible on SW side and N side, crumbled down on W side, partly vanished and/or covered by earth from the mound. At SW side, two horizontal layers of tufa chips can be distinguished at 112 cm. above modern ground level. On top of wall large blocks of basalt define the upper ring. At some spots, most notable at W and N side, modern fill of mainly large basalt blocks with some tufa and white marble pieces. Height  of Roman wall as visible on SW-side 220 cm, thickness of wall at SW side 75 cm. \r\nEarthwork of the tumulus originally probably half round, but highly eroded and covered with weed, some shrubs and blocks of stone, mostly basalt. Mountain bike path is crossing E side of tumulus.\r\nDimensions of the tumulus as a whole. Diameter 17.5 m, H. mound 6 m, with tower 10 m, base cylinder 3 m. The tomb contained a travertine block with a cylindrical cavity Pinza 1907, fig. 63; Eisner). In front of the tumulus there was a paved space. Architectural elements belonging to it were executed in marble (here sites ###). In the centre on top of the tumulus stands a round tower, made of brickwork of mostly square rectangular tufa  blocks, put together with reddish mortar full of cruma. Blocks are laid in regular horizontal layers. Some diagonal blocks of tufa are visible on the inside, possible markers for day works. Outside covered with reddish mortar, inside not covered. Outside mortar in four horizontal layers. Top of the tower is broken off, two holes in tower wall at W and NW side. Lower part of tower possibly covered by earthwork of tumulus. Thickness of walls: 60 cm. diameter tower at the outside 295 cm., at the inside 175 cm. Brick work of tower seems to be medieval with possible modern mortar at the outside, no indications of Roman building elements in the tower. Tower is seen as structure to consolidate the mass of the tumulus, but could also be a medieval watch tower. Most scholars (Pinza, Quilici, Coarelli, Eisner) consider the tower as an original part of the monument and date it to the time of construction: it would reinforce the tumulus and have been covered by the sand mound of the tumulus. Eisner suggests that the cinerary urn could have found accommodation here. Similar constructions are known from the Mausoleum of Augustus and the mausoleum of Sempronius Atratinus at Gaeta.\r\nAccording to Canina and, later, De Rossi (1969) the tower was built in the 13th or 14th century. Prof. S. de Blaauw, who visited the monument in July 2012, also sees it as a medieval or even 16th-century structure.               ', E'Funerary', E'Tumulus', NULL, '2014-08-01 17:34:24', NULL, E'three objects, 5-7-12, \r\nShort description: large tumulus style funerary monument, so-called tomb of the Curiatii. Location: W of Via Appia, N of crossing with dirt road to the Via Pompeo Licino.Tumulus shaped funerary monument, no platform visible. Composed of a circular wall filled in with earth.');
