INSERT INTO "tbl1_site" ("Site_ID", "Administrator", "Modern_composition", "Description_site", "Site_context", "Site_interpretation_keyword", "Site_interpretation", "Date_entry", "description_m_composition", "Description_site_OLD") VALUES (434, NULL, E'0', E'Large circular tomb on rectangular base, probably smaller version of the type of tomb of Caecilia Metella. Core of base and circular building present, no original facing left. Heavily restructured in medieval times, modern interventions. \r\nPlatform (described from the bottom up): at S side strip of concrete merely composed of basalt and mortar, small extension at E side with the same materials, but with some reddish tufa blocks. In E end of S side some reddish tufa and travertine added in concrete. Remainder of lower layer of plateau is composed of reddish tufa, some basalt and mortar. On top of the lower layer of the platform are two more layers, each topped by a thin layer of travertine splitters. Second and third layer from greyish mortar with small elements of red tufa, blocks of red and yellow tufa and some travertine. Outlines of the plateau are no longer visible, dimensions unknown (Eisner: 10.7 x 12 x 3 m)..\r\nRound tomb structure: consists of concrete core composed of three layers of yellow and reddish tufa blocks with mortar, above this a top layer which mainly consists of basalt and travertine. Concrete core at the outside covered with smooth wall in masonry of the same material, which covers the whole S and SE side of the round structure and the lower part of the W side. In lower part at W side is a small window. Possible medieval restoration. Above layer of masonry at W side are three abutments to support Roman concrete, possibly a modern restoration. Diameter 8 m, H. 8 m.\r\nBig hole in NE side closed with wall roughly made of blocks of basalt, grey tufa, marble and travertine, post antique, possibly modern. Hole might have  been post-antique door or window.  Same holds for window? hole at NW side. In SW corner entrance with iron fence, which runs through Roman concrete and medieval/modern masonry.\r\nInterior: open space without a roof and without traces of vault, concrete visible at most places. At S side covering with opus reticulatum visible in yellow and reddish tufa. Floor covered with modern concrete, in centre of floor hole to pit or hollow room. \r\nOn top and partly inside round wall arches are build on NE and SW side with joining pieces of wall. Above both arches are small windows. Arches composed of probably ancient brick tiles. Wall portion at SW arch opus vittatum mixtum of basalt, tufa, marble and travertine, alternated with double layers of bricks. Masonry surrounding NE arch mainly basalt, pieces or marble and some brick, not laid out in clear horizontal lines. Arches at NE and SW side possible medieval additions.\r\nSite 552, inscription of Arelius Glabra has been connected with this tomb.\r\nSchwarz dates the monument to the Imperial period on the basis of its dimensions.\r\nIn early discussions this tomb is ascribed to Quintus Caecilius, the uncle of Pompeius Atticus whose tomb would be here according to Nepos, Life of Atticus 22 (Pratilli; Nibby).\r\nNowadays connected with our site 552, inscription of Arellius Glabra.                 ', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2014-08-07 18:34:48', NULL, E'11 july 2012\r\nLarge round tombe on rectangular base\r\nW of Via Appia, SW of Laterizio 1 and 2');
