INSERT INTO "tbl1_site" ("Site_ID", "Administrator", "Modern_composition", "Description_site", "Site_context", "Site_interpretation_keyword", "Site_interpretation", "Date_entry", "description_m_composition", "Description_site_OLD") VALUES (696, NULL, E'0', E'At west side remains of a rectangular chamber tomb consisting of two rooms. Constructed in opus latericium with a concrete core. At the east side a large roughly cut hole opens onto the interior of a rectangular room, nowadays filled with bramble shrubs. The south wall is not preserved to a visible height, the west wall is invisible, whereas the north wall is discretely preserved. The entrance must have been at the west side. The brickwork is fine at the north side and the northern part of the east side, with regular bricks and thin layers of mortar (modulus of five tiers 23 at north and 22 at east, north side), while that of the east wall for the greater part is rough (modulus 26.5 cm).\r\nA small chamber follows at the north side. Remains of an L-shaped wall preserved, which continues towards the east, with a large interruption (or door) in front of the modern hole in the east wall of the tomb chamber. This wall shows the same fine brickwork described before (modulus east wall, north side 20.5 cm; south side 19.5 cm). The southern stretch has a plinth with a fine profile, heavily damaged. This shows a cyma recta. At the north side a small stretch has been added, which seems to continue in the dividing wall.\r\nIn front of the eastern wall of the west tomb, on a lower level there is a structure in the shape of an H, forming a small chamber at the west side and two niches at the east side. The brickwork is coarser and is similar to that of the east wall of the burial chamber (modulus north façade 25 cm, interior east side 25 cm, south façade 25 cm).\r\nThe niches at the east side are separated by a modern wall of red bricks placed on top of two ancient tufa block. It supports a vault made of opus caementicium. The interior walls of the niches consist of four layers of concrete, alternatively containing basalt and tufa. It is not clear whether they are ancient or modern interventions. The core of the vault contains basalt                 ', E'Funerary', E'Funerary monument (generic)', NULL, '2014-07-30 10:46:46', NULL, E'13-7-2013\r\none object\r\n\r\nGroup of two funerary monuments, partly restored in modern times. Some parts covered by shrubs and weed, front injured and in decay. \r\nLocation: at east and west sides of 19th-century division wall.');
